Best food , cheeses, desert and wines I had ever had in entire life with greet attentive yet balanced service. The wine selection is some of the best. The Sommelier was very knowledgeable. Ambiance is comfortable but not Goddy. We were able to enjoy a good meal and have casual conversation and hear each other.

I have to be honest, I had VERY HIGH expectation for the restaurants because of their yelp review, but maybe because of my high expectations, everything was a bit of a disappointment. We were able to snag a 8pm seating on Sunday. I've been looking forward to this restaurant for a while and canceled our other reservation because we were able to finally book this one. It actually started of not too bad. We were greeted warmly and were able to be seated right away although we arrived just a tad earlier. The seating in the restaurant is rather crowded. Feel like they tried to fid too much seats here, but again we were seated in the corner so it's quite comfortable. The food ordered is actually not that memorable. As of now (5 days later) I actually can't really recall what I ate and had to look through my photos. What I ordered: 1. Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar 2. Lobster 3. Lamb 4. Lemon souffle. Overall the food are quite salty and heavy. I think, don't order the oysters, didn't think it was that fresh. The lobster was OKAY but again, not memorable. The lamb was not too bad. It comes in layers of lamb, veggies and eggplant. Again, on the salty side. Portion size is pretty big. The souffle was definitely pretty good after all the saltiness consumed. Honestly, I think food is personal taste. Some people find the food here great, but I don't. I just don't see anything special about it. Service was meh. Actually there's a few waiter that are quite good in between, but the main one who's around us most of the time is not. I'm not saying he's impolite, but the way he serves seems like he doesn't care. He pour our wine as if he is rushed and just dumped in our wine glasses instead of pouring is slowly like the other waiter. He was a lot more attentive to the new customers who came in when we were about to be done. No, I don't know his name, or I don't care to give him a shoutout here even if I do know. But for what we were spending, I definitely think that the service here should be better.

Came here with my sis and mom when they visited sf last weekend. My sis called in for a reservation 3 weeks prior to the visit. She got a 9:30pm reservation. It was late but she took it anyway. Two days upon arrival, they called to confirm her reservation, she then asked if they have another time slot...and they did, one for 530pm. We took it, of course! So our reservation experience was alot painless and hassleless compared to what I've read on yelp. We just got really lucky too!! Seriously though, the service here is one of the best I've ever received. Like omg!! I guess this is what it feels like to be royalty??? We got seated immediately when we got there. The minute we sat down, the waiter unfolded the napkins and put it on our laps, asked if we wanted tap or sparkling water. And then the bread guy comes right away with the bread and butter. Seriously, the entire 2 hrs, my plate never went without a bread on it. All three of us got the 3 courses option for 87 dollars, which was worth it!! We all got something different so I was able to try 9 different dishes. Yasssss! You basically get to pick 3, 4 or 5 dishes of any courses on the menu. Even the starter and desserts are big portions! So don't feel like your wasting money if you pick 1 starter and 1 dessert...it's enough to fill you up. Food here was amazinggggg! My first course was the tuna. Presentation was beautiful, it looked like a butterfly. It was so pretty, I felt bad digging in. I picked two entrees, I got the duck and the main lobster. Both were delicious!! I would definitely come back. For 3 people, with 2 glasses of wine, and tax and tip, it came out to be about 350. Service was top notch!!! Felt like I was a queen here.

I wanted to jump on the bandwagon of giving Gary Danko a 5-star, but I'd betray myself if I do so. (Maybe I was expecting too much out of Gary Danko?) I wanted to love my experience at GD, but let me put it this way: if you've never been to GD and you think that perhaps you're missing out--well hun, you're not. But a once in a while visit would be luxurious enough. OK LET'S TALK FOOD For starters, they provided us with yellow beets for amuse bouche, and I'd say, I'll order this by itself as an appetizer if only it was on the menu! It was so good! I had the 5-course menu consisting of the following: 1) Cured Foie Gras Torchon with Roasted Grapes, Candied Peanuts, & Honey Tuille - This is below the best foie gras I've ever tasted! The perfect foie gras torchon is supposed to kinda melt on your tongue like a creamy butter. Ths one was served cold as it should be. Yes, foie gras torchon is the kind of thing that's gotta be served as cold as possible, but then when you do serve it, you gotta provide a warm knife. That way the foie gras kinda melts in the mouth. You know what I mean? Well, they did the former but not the latter. (Again, like I said, perhaps I was expecting too much.) ------------------------------- 2) Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing - Came with 4 slices aesthetically placed to look like a tuna butterfly (cute!), the two bigger portions had a rich bright red color, which was the most desirable. The two smaller ones (patched with the nori) had a brownish color when I flipped it. The taste wasn't the freshest. I traded this one with my friend's plate and I ate his pan-seared bass plate instead. ------------------------------- 3) Pan Seared Bass with Israeli Couscous, Broccoli, Glazed Turnips, and Radish (5/5) - Oh, my goodness, thank you for this saving grace! The pan seared bass was cooked to perfection, and the couscous is probably the best version I've ever tasted of it. Mixed together, they were exploding with tastiness and flavor, I was wowed. ------------------------------- 4) Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon - Small lobster portion enough to fill my tiny body. The lobster was tender cooked saturated with tasty potato puree. It was good. ------------------------------- 5) Grand Marnier Souffle with Creamsicle Ice Cream and Two Sauces (raspberry and something else) - a really pale version of souffle that spent time in the oven just the right amount of time. It was not too airy, nice texture, deftly sweetened... I ate it all by myself! Heh. ------------------------------- NOW LET'S TALK SERVICE - They offer coat check-ins and valet service. - They didn't ask for my ID when I ordered wine--I'm impressed. Other restaurants are fooled by my Asian genes. GD staff didn't bother. - They serve complimentary bread, which was quite boring frankly, it was a waste of time -_- - They give you a little cake if you made your reservation and told them it was for a celebration. It was my best friend's birthday, so I got to blow the cake candle for him. Haha. - Their bathroom looks elegant, like, why is there a chair beside the toilet seat?? There are reasons to this of course. - Our server(s) weren't really personable, they were like in "all-business mode" and that wasn't very friendly or welcoming. - They give you little takeaway desserts (pastries) wrapped in a golden package so that you'll remember them even when you get home. Kind of like, to reinforce the unforgettable dining experience you had last night.

This is the number one reason, obviously. Cheese cart is bae.

I must say the food service and ambiance is the tops. Denise our excellent coordinator for the meal was outstanding, his ability to please and focus on details was outstanding. Not hard to see why Gary Danko is so popular.

Superb. Gary Danko was the best dining experience we had in SF and surpassed by expectations. It wasn't cheap, but it was worth every penny. Attire - dressy, though being the bay area, it was less formal than I expected (I'm from DC). Business casual is appropriate. I wore a sports coat and no tie and felt perfectly comfortable. Service - perfection. Warm and personable, with a big dose of California friendliness. Portions - I always get worried at tasting menu places that I'll be looking for pizza afterwards. Not at Gary Danko. The portions were more than generous, and the four course menu left us stuffed. Also, what I think is brilliant is the portions are proportionate to the number of courses you order, so if you order the three course you don't have to worry about leaving hungry since the servings will actually be on the larger size than the five course. Standouts - risotto with shrimp and crab, branzini, bison, and duck breast. All were exceptional. The butter cake was lovely, though perhaps a tad over-hyped, but the Grand Marnier souffle was divine. Mignardises were served with the bill, and we were sent home with a scrumptious banana bread for the next day.

I came here to celebrate my boyfriend's birthday a little early. Pretty difficult to find parking as you can expect. It was super cold that evening and we were lucky enough to snag a parking spot only a block and a half away. They offer valet service for $20 if you aren't lucky with parking. The restaurant's exterior wasn't what I had imagined for some reason. You couldn't see anything in the restaurant as all the windows were tinted black. We were in for a surprise, but a wonderful one. It was very elegant inside. We came a few minutes past our reservation time as we made a quick pit stop to Patagonia a block away. Our reservation time was 5:30 which was when they opened. I was surprised to see so many people sitting down already. That was fast. You have the option of choosing the tasting menu or a 3-4-5 course meal. We went for the 4-course meal. What I loved about this option was that even though you were given the option of appetizers, seafood, meats, and desserts, you could choose four of ANYTHING. It doesn't necessarily have to go in what you'd think as the proper sequence (appetizer, entree, dessert), although you could do it that way if you wanted to. It could be four entrees... all lobster if you wanted! I skipped out on the appetizers and went straight to the entrees, heh. Originally I had ordered four entrees, BUT when I got to my third course, I started getting a bit full. Luckily, they were still able to change my fourth course into a dessert rather than the seared filet of beef I had ordered. The waiter recommended getting a dessert when I was placing my initial order as my fourth course since it was my first time, but I definitely overestimated my appetite and turned down the dessert option. He knew all along, ha. Anyways - what I had ordered was the roast maine lobster, seared sea scallops, lemon pepper duck breast, and the chocolate souffle with two sauces. I think my top two favorites were the scallops and the duck breast. Both were so tender. Although the lobster was good (such a drastic change from the horrible overcooked lobster I had at that buffet in Reno omg), lobster never seems to wow me just because I've never been a huge fan of it. My boyfriend order the roast maine lobster, coconut thai curry with an assortment of seafood, herb crusted loin of lamb, and the duck breast as well. His coconut thai curry tasted more like a bisque than it did curry, but was still very good. I definitely wouldn't have ordered dessert as my fourth course if I knew we were going to be served an assortment of tiny desserts along with the free birthday dessert for my boyfriend. At the end of our meal, we were given these nicely packaged desserts to take home with us. They were banana cream cheese cakes I believe! Honestly, I would have been content with a 3-course meal.. it was too much food for one night! I guess it really depends on what you order and how hungry you really are. Food was great, definitely super filling if you order the right things. Service was top notch. That's the one thing that stood out the most for me. Water was refilled almost instantly. And so was the bread. I found it kind of funny that my bread was refilled within a second of grabbing my final piece. They were so on top of everything, I loved it! Definitely a great place to celebrate a special occasion!

Gary Danko has been on my list to try for quite awhile, so I finally got off my lazy butt and made a reservation far in advance to celebrate Valentine's Day and our engagement anniversary! In a nutshell, while the food was good, I think it was slightly overhyped in my head AND the fact that I was eating with my eyes and opted for the 5 course menu which made me way too full probably slowed down my appreciation for the food later on in the meal. That being said, I *would* come back. Food was definitely solid but not every dish was out of this world. Service was superb as can be expected for a Michelin star restaurant. I actually didn't know Gary Danko had a star until I googled it--just thought it was really good fine dining! For starters, they take reservations up to 2 months in advance. If you have your heart really set on a date, call sooner rather than later as last year my husband tried booking a reservation with only 2 weeks til the date and it was impossible. Groups of 6 will require a card on file. The menu is either pre-set tasting or customize your own, which is pretty fabulous for us because my husband is more picky whereas I'm more adventurous. Like I said, we opted for 5 courses ($124pp), but I think next time 3 courses ($87pp) would be perfect...4 courses ($104pp) could be pushing the envelope a bit. But if you have a big appetite, by all means, go for more courses! I started with foie gras torchon topped with pistachios which I spread across a delicious country toast paired with an amazing fruity jam. I can't remember the spread but it had honey and yuzu-like flavors. An unlikely pairing but that richness of salt-cured foie gras was cut through by the sweetness and I savored every bite. The waiter recommended to try this over the seared foie gras, which I'd be curious to try next time because I'm a fan of FG! Hubby got pan-seared scallops (2) with parsnip puree, cauliflower, and like 2-3 brussel sprout leaves. That puree...that sear. Mm...I'm so glad I got my own plate of this for my second course because I didn't really want to share..haha this was one of my favorites. Hubby's second course was the coconut thai curry with calamari, shrimp, lobster, scallops, etc. They plate it in front of you so your rice doesn't get soggy...that curry broth was so rich yet light and flavorful...I just wanted to drink it for days! I tend not to order curries because we have so much Asian food in general already, but I'm glad the waiter recommended this and it WAS good :) My third course was the branzini with fennel puree and blood-orange saffron emulsion. This fish was fried to a perfect crisp and another one of my favorites! Licked the plate clean, I kid you not. Hubby's third course was the lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash and bacon braise endive. I also got this as my 4th course. I have to say, though the duck was cooked perfectly, the flavors didn't stand out as much to me and by this time I was getting SO full. My husband liked it more than me though. This was a pretty heavily portioned dish and so I ended up taking most of it home after a few bites. My husband got bison as his last order and it came with a giant oyster mushroom and herb-infused green spaetzel. We had never had spaetzel before and seriously thought it was veggies. But the texture was great and it was lightly flavored...couldn't stop nibbling on it. I wasn't as impressed with bison but it was also my first time trying bison and I think probably the last...not really my thing. Hubby said it was slightly tough to chew and ended up taking half of his home too to save room for dessert. For dessert, I got the lemon souffle cake with panna cotta and raspberry sorbet. I thought it would be more of a souffle but it was more of a dense cake. I loved the panna cotta, but this was a little too tart with the raspberry sorbet for me. Hubby got grand marnier souffle which they plated beautifully in front of him. This was pretty delicious but maybe too citrusy for me. The vanilla ice cream on top helped a bit though. They also brought us a plated chocolate cake with "Happy Anniversary" written on it and a candle, along with a tiny platter of the cutest mini desserts. I appreciated this a lot even though I don't really like chocolate. We had fun sampling the mini tarts and bites too but it was not that mind-blowing. Lastly they gave us banana cream cheese cake to take home for breakfast, which is always a nice touch! All in all, it was a great experience, but I'm going to reserve a star because I think I'll go back to try more and hopefully be a little more blown away like some of the other Michelin restaurants I've had :) Reserve about 3 hours for 5-courses. You can valet or look for parking in the area but a lot of the meters are only 2 hours. We ended up parking in the Ghirardelli square lot.

We had the chocolate soufflé and creme brûlée trio. Both were very good as expected. The Monastrell dessert wine was very good as well. So why the one star? Quite possibly one of the most unnecessarily rude experiences of my life via the maître d'. After getting seated at our table (at 10pm mind you, so far from primetime dinner hours), I informed the waiter that we would just be doing dessert. He apparently relayed that information to the maître d' who took it upon himself to come by, in full view and earshot of the other nearby tables, and tell my girlfriend and I that we would've never gotten that table if he had known we were only doing dessert. However, he would let it slide just this once but don't go telling our friends that this is a thing here. Unreal. Naturally, that was an embarrassing exchange and cast an uncomfortable shadow over the rest of our meal. A meal that was supposed to be a nice little ending to our 12 day trip with our flight back to reality the following morning. If we were going to be allowed to keep the table anyway, what was the point of saying anything? If he really felt it necessary, he could've mentioned it with some discretion as we were leaving. I understand the concern of sticking a waiter with a lower value table, which is why I was already planning on leaving (and actually did despite the rude treatment) a +30% tip for our 30 minutes of the restaurant's time at the end of their service. We also didn't just order one dessert to split with two waters for a $20 bill. The whole situation was handled incredibly poorly. It's also worth noting that nowhere on their website or OpenTable is there any indication that reserving a table for only dessert isn't allowed. Again, being aware of the drawbacks to both the restaurant and waiter, we purposely booked a late table and spent a decent amount between our 2 desserts and wine plus hefty tip, while also not lingering very long. Apparently, conscientiousness is a one way street at this restaurant.

    I have to be honest, I had VERY HIGH expectation for the restaurants because of their yelp review, but maybe because of my high expectations, everything was a bit of a disappointment.

    We were able to snag a 8pm seating on Sunday. I've been looking forward to this restaurant for a while and canceled our other reservation because we were able to finally book this one. It actually started of not too bad. We were greeted warmly and were able to be seated right away although we arrived just a tad earlier. The seating in the restaurant is rather crowded. Feel like they tried to fid too much seats here, but again we were seated in the corner so it's quite comfortable.

    The food ordered is actually not that memorable. As of now (5 days later) I actually can't really recall what I ate and had to look through my photos.

    What I ordered:
    1. Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar
    2. Lobster
    3. Lamb
    4. Lemon souffle.

    Overall the food are quite salty and heavy. I think, don't order the oysters, didn't think it was that fresh. The lobster was OKAY but again, not memorable. The lamb was not too bad. It comes in layers of lamb, veggies and eggplant. Again, on the salty side. Portion size is pretty big. The souffle was definitely pretty good after all the saltiness consumed. Honestly, I think food is personal taste. Some people find the food here great, but I don't. I just don't see anything special about it.

    Service was meh. Actually there's a few waiter that are quite good in between, but the main one who's around us most of the time is not. I'm not saying he's impolite, but the way he serves seems like he doesn't care. He pour our wine as if he is rushed and just dumped in our wine glasses instead of pouring is slowly like the other waiter. He was a lot more attentive to the new customers who came in when we were about to be done. No, I don't know his name, or I don't care to give him a shoutout here even if I do know. But for what we were spending, I definitely think that the service here should be better.

    1 check-in

    I wanted to jump on the bandwagon of giving Gary Danko a 5-star, but I'd betray myself if I do so. (Maybe I was expecting too much out of Gary Danko?) I wanted to love my experience at GD, but let me put it this way: if you've never been to GD and you think that perhaps you're missing out--well hun, you're not. But a once in a while visit would be luxurious enough.  

    OK LET'S TALK FOOD
    For starters, they provided us with yellow beets for amuse bouche, and I'd say, I'll order this by itself as an appetizer if only it was on the menu! It was so good!

    I had the 5-course menu consisting of the following:

    1) Cured Foie Gras Torchon with Roasted Grapes, Candied Peanuts, & Honey Tuille
    - This is below the best foie gras I've ever tasted! The perfect foie gras torchon is supposed to kinda melt on your tongue like a creamy butter. Ths one was served cold as it should be. Yes, foie gras torchon is the kind of thing that's gotta be served as cold as possible, but then when you do serve it, you gotta provide a warm knife. That way the foie gras kinda melts in the mouth. You know what I mean? Well, they did the former but not the latter. (Again, like I said, perhaps I was expecting too much.)
    -------------------------------
    2) Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing
    - Came with 4 slices aesthetically placed to look like a tuna butterfly (cute!), the two bigger portions had a rich bright red color, which was the most desirable. The two smaller ones (patched with the nori) had a brownish color when I flipped it. The taste wasn't the freshest. I traded this one with my friend's plate and I ate his pan-seared bass plate instead.
    -------------------------------
    3) Pan Seared Bass with Israeli Couscous, Broccoli, Glazed Turnips, and Radish (5/5)
    - Oh, my goodness, thank you for this saving grace! The pan seared bass was cooked to perfection, and the couscous is probably the best version I've ever tasted of it. Mixed together, they were exploding with tastiness and flavor, I was wowed.
    -------------------------------
    4) Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon
    - Small lobster portion enough to fill my tiny body. The lobster was tender cooked saturated with tasty potato puree. It was good.
    -------------------------------
    5) Grand Marnier Souffle with Creamsicle Ice Cream and Two Sauces (raspberry and something else)
    - a really pale version of souffle that spent time in the oven just the right amount of time. It was not too airy, nice texture, deftly sweetened... I ate it all by myself! Heh.
    -------------------------------
    NOW LET'S TALK SERVICE
    - They offer coat check-ins and valet service.
    - They didn't ask for my ID when I ordered wine--I'm impressed. Other restaurants are fooled by my Asian genes. GD staff didn't bother.
    - They serve complimentary bread, which was quite boring frankly, it was a waste of time -_-
    - They give you a little cake if you made your reservation and told them it was for a celebration. It was my best friend's birthday, so I got to blow the cake candle for him. Haha.
    - Their bathroom looks elegant, like, why is there a chair beside the toilet seat?? There are reasons to this of course.
    - Our server(s) weren't really personable, they were like in "all-business mode" and that wasn't very friendly or welcoming.
    - They give you little takeaway desserts (pastries) wrapped in a golden package so that you'll remember them even when you get home. Kind of like, to reinforce the unforgettable dining experience you had last night.

    3/30/2018

    Superb.  Gary Danko was the best dining experience we had in SF and surpassed by expectations.  It wasn't cheap, but it was worth every penny.

    Attire - dressy, though being the bay area, it was less formal than I expected (I'm from DC).  Business casual is appropriate.  I wore a sports coat and no tie and felt perfectly comfortable.

    Service - perfection.  Warm and personable, with a big dose of California friendliness.

    Portions - I always get worried at tasting menu places that I'll be looking for pizza afterwards.  Not at Gary Danko.  The portions were more than generous, and the four course menu left us stuffed.  Also, what I think is brilliant is the portions are proportionate to the number of courses you order, so if you order the three course you don't have to worry about leaving hungry since the servings will actually be on the larger size than the five course.

    Standouts - risotto with shrimp and crab, branzini, bison, and duck breast.  All were exceptional.  The butter cake was lovely, though perhaps a tad over-hyped, but the Grand Marnier souffle was divine.  Mignardises were served with the bill, and we were sent home with a scrumptious banana bread for the next day.

    I came here to celebrate my boyfriend's birthday a little early. Pretty difficult to find parking as you can expect. It was super cold that evening and we were lucky enough to snag a parking spot only a block and a half away. They offer valet service for $20 if you aren't lucky with parking.

    The restaurant's exterior wasn't what I had imagined for some reason. You couldn't see anything in the restaurant as all the windows were tinted black. We were in for a surprise, but a wonderful one. It was very elegant inside. We came a few minutes past our reservation time as we made a quick pit stop to Patagonia a block away. Our reservation time was 5:30 which was when they opened. I was surprised to see so many people sitting down already. That was fast.

    You have the option of choosing the tasting menu or a 3-4-5 course meal. We went for the 4-course meal. What I loved about this option was that even though you were given the option of appetizers, seafood, meats, and desserts, you could choose four of ANYTHING. It doesn't necessarily have to go in what you'd think as the proper sequence (appetizer, entree, dessert), although you could do it that way if you wanted to. It could be four entrees... all lobster if you wanted! I skipped out on the appetizers and went straight to the entrees, heh.

    Originally I had ordered four entrees, BUT when I got to my third course, I started getting a bit full. Luckily, they were still able to change my fourth course into a dessert rather than the seared filet of beef I had ordered. The waiter recommended getting a dessert when I was placing my initial order as my fourth course since it was my first time, but I definitely overestimated my appetite and turned down the dessert option. He knew all along, ha. Anyways - what I had ordered was the roast maine lobster, seared sea scallops, lemon pepper duck breast, and the chocolate souffle with two sauces. I think my top two favorites were the scallops and the duck breast. Both were so tender. Although the lobster was good (such a drastic change from the horrible overcooked lobster I had at that buffet in Reno omg), lobster never seems to wow me just because I've never been a huge fan of it. My boyfriend order the roast maine lobster, coconut thai curry with an assortment of seafood, herb crusted loin of lamb, and the duck breast as well. His coconut thai curry tasted more like a bisque than it did curry, but was still very good. I definitely wouldn't have ordered dessert as my fourth course if I knew we were going to be served an assortment of tiny desserts along with the free birthday dessert for my boyfriend.

    At the end of our meal, we were given these nicely packaged desserts to take home with us. They were banana cream cheese cakes I believe!

    Honestly, I would have been content with a 3-course meal.. it was too much food for one night! I guess it really depends on what you order and how hungry you really are.

    Food was great, definitely super filling if you order the right things. Service was top notch. That's the one thing that stood out the most for me. Water was refilled almost instantly. And so was the bread. I found it kind of funny that my bread was refilled within a second of grabbing my final piece. They were so on top of everything, I loved it!

    Definitely a great place to celebrate a special occasion!

    1 check-in

    Gary Danko has been on my list to try for quite awhile, so I finally got off my lazy butt and made a reservation far in advance to celebrate Valentine's Day and our engagement anniversary! In a nutshell, while the food was good, I think it was slightly overhyped in my head AND the fact that I was eating with my eyes and opted for the 5 course menu which made me way too full probably slowed down my appreciation for the food later on in the meal. That being said, I *would* come back. Food was definitely solid but not every dish was out of this world. Service was superb as can be expected for a Michelin star restaurant. I actually didn't know Gary Danko had a star until I googled it--just thought it was really good fine dining!

    For starters, they take reservations up to 2 months in advance. If you have your heart really set on a date, call sooner rather than later as last year my husband tried booking a reservation with only 2 weeks til the date and it was impossible. Groups of 6 will require a card on file. The menu is either pre-set tasting or customize your own, which is pretty fabulous for us because my husband is more picky whereas I'm more adventurous. Like I said, we opted for 5 courses ($124pp), but I think next time 3 courses ($87pp) would be perfect...4 courses ($104pp) could be pushing the envelope a bit. But if you have a big appetite, by all means, go for more courses!

    I started with foie gras torchon topped with pistachios which I spread across a delicious country toast paired with an amazing fruity jam. I can't remember the spread but it had honey and yuzu-like flavors. An unlikely pairing but that richness of salt-cured foie gras was cut through by the sweetness and I savored every bite. The waiter recommended to try this over the seared foie gras, which I'd be curious to try next time because I'm a fan of FG!

    Hubby got pan-seared scallops (2) with parsnip puree, cauliflower, and like 2-3 brussel sprout leaves. That puree...that sear. Mm...I'm so glad I got my own plate of this for my second course because I didn't really want to share..haha this was one of my favorites.

    Hubby's second course was the coconut thai curry with calamari, shrimp, lobster, scallops, etc. They plate it in front of you so your rice doesn't get soggy...that curry broth was so rich yet light and flavorful...I just wanted to drink it for days! I tend not to order curries because we have so much Asian food in general already, but I'm glad the waiter recommended this and it WAS good :)

    My third course was the branzini with fennel puree and blood-orange saffron emulsion. This fish was fried to a perfect crisp and another one of my favorites! Licked the plate clean, I kid you not.

    Hubby's third course was the lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash and bacon braise endive. I also got this as my 4th course. I have to say, though the duck was cooked perfectly, the flavors didn't stand out as much to me and by this time I was getting SO full. My husband liked it more than me though. This was a pretty heavily portioned dish and so I ended up taking most of it home after a few bites.

    My husband got bison as his last order and it came with a giant oyster mushroom and herb-infused green spaetzel. We had never had spaetzel before and seriously thought it was veggies. But the texture was great and it was lightly flavored...couldn't stop nibbling on it. I wasn't as impressed with bison but it was also my first time trying bison and I think probably the last...not really my thing. Hubby said it was slightly tough to chew and ended up taking half of his home too to save room for dessert.

    For dessert, I got the lemon souffle cake with panna cotta and raspberry sorbet. I thought it would be more of a souffle but it was more of a dense cake. I loved the panna cotta, but this was a little too tart with the raspberry sorbet for me. Hubby got grand marnier souffle which they plated beautifully in front of him. This was pretty delicious but maybe too citrusy for me. The vanilla ice cream on top helped a bit though.

    They also brought us a plated chocolate cake with "Happy Anniversary" written on it and a candle, along with a tiny platter of the cutest mini desserts. I appreciated this a lot even though I don't really like chocolate. We had fun sampling the mini tarts and bites too but it was not that mind-blowing.

    Lastly they gave us banana cream cheese cake to take home for breakfast, which is always a nice touch! All in all, it was a great experience, but I'm going to reserve a star because I think I'll go back to try more and hopefully be a little more blown away like some of the other Michelin restaurants I've had :)

    Reserve about 3 hours for 5-courses. You can valet or look for parking in the area but a lot of the meters are only 2 hours. We ended up parking in the Ghirardelli square lot.
